No, apparently not. The creature hissed only and tried to fly directly towards Thassalin. Fortunately, Thassalin was nimble enough despite his size and dodged, but Nyssi let out a cry as she almost lost her grip on Thassalin's smooth scales.
„HOW CAN WE KILL THEM?“, screamed Nyssi.
„AIM FOR THEIR HEADS!“
„THAT WILL BE DIFFICULT!“
Thassalin hissed and then drew a circle, closer to the mountain he called home. The dark beast followed, but got slightly panicky when it was hit by a fire beam from behind. It had not realized that it was no longer alone. It got even more panicky when Thassalin slowed down and then flung his tail against her head, throwing her off course.
Growling and hissing, it flew upward and spat into the air. Everything suddenly became dark, as if the monster sucked the light from the sky into itself and replaced it with a cloud of eternal night.
When he could no longer see anything, Thassalin tried to retreat. He felt himself scraping along the tree crowns before finally crashing into a clearing. The beast seemed to know exactly where he had fallen and shot directly at him, dragging the black cloud with it.
„Kayel!“, screamed Tenuk as he glided out of the cloud and began circling to look for Nyssi and Thassalin in the darkness below. „What should we do now, Kayel…? Kayel, where are you?“
Below, Nyssi struggled to her feet. She was sure she had broken something, but her peculiar, supernatural healing powers had already begun to take effect. Unfortunately, this did not apply to Thassalin. He leaned exhausted against the only tree that had not collapsed under his weight. Nyssi tried her best to get close to Thassalin, but she could barely see two meters. Everything was pitch black and shrouded in eerie shadows. And in that shadow, something was screaming and screeching.
A terrifying, armored tail crashed beside Nyssi on the ground and knocked her down. However, she noticed that the tail was just wildly flailing and not intentionally trying to hit her. The beast, or rather the little that Nyssi could see and hear of it, growled and slashed at the shadows it had created with its claws. Something shot through the darkness, pierced the monster, and confused it.
Suddenly, a gunshot cracked through the mist, and the monster fell silent, collapsed to the ground, and lay motionless. The darkness around them dissolved, and they saw what had happened: Kayel stood on the beast, heavily panting as he held his rifle.
„That was… probably the weirdest shadow leap I’ve ever made… Thanto kat’olon…“, Kabel gasped for breath. His eyes glowed almost black, and a dark energy swirled around his body. But while he was still speaking, color returned to his armor, and his eyes took on their normal yellow color again.
It took a moment for Nyssi to understand what had happened. They had all known that Kayel possessed these strange shadow powers. He rarely used them, because most people found them creepy and quite intimidating. But Nyssi had not known that Kayel could also use these powers in any kind of darkness. And the way Kayel was behaving, he apparently was also quite surprised.
„Are you okay?“, broke out of Nyssi.
„Yes, I’m fine. I killed something, I’ll be back to normal soon.“ Kayel looked at his work as Tenuk flew down, landed beside him, and once again took on his normal spastic form.
Now that the beast was no longer moving, they could see better what it was. Its skin was raven-black and slimy, but the slime remained firmly attached to its body. It had four wings and four extremities, all ending in long, thin claws, and two straight horns protruded from its skull.
Before Tenuk and Kayel could ask what the hell they were looking at, something screeched and jumped out of a nearby bush. However, it did not reach them, because a familiar vehicle crashed into its side and caused the monster to skid to a stop in front of Nyssi's feet. Nyssi wanted to take no chances. She grabbed her shotgun, fired without thinking at its head, and the creature died on the spot.
„Oops…“, muttered Retvik from the driver's seat before he awkwardly turned off the engine and got out of the truck. „Uh, that wasn't intentional. Are you all okay?“
„You missed all the action“, scolded Tenuk. „Where were you?“
„You all just left me standing there. I came as fast as I could…“, sighed Retvik. „May I ask what those terrible creatures are?“
Fortunately, Retvik's question was answered by Thassalin, who had managed to get back on his feet. He was covered in cuts and scratches and seemed a bit dazed, but not seriously injured.
„YOU KILLED THE CORRUPTIIDS! THE INFECTED MONSTERS. BEINGS THAT WERE WEGGING HERE WHEN THE CORRUPTION ATTACKED YOUR GODS.“
„You mean that terrible god-monster creature that we… helped kill?“, stuttered Tenuk.
„YES. EXACTLY THAT. THERE MAY BE MORE. BUT I COULD NOT SHOOT IN THE HEAD. I HAVE NO FIREARM. AND TWO AGAINST ONE IS UNFAIR, OR?“ Thassalin hobbled to Kayel and patted his head. „THANK YOU VERY MUCH, LITTLE ONE. YOU REMIND ME OF MY OLD FRIEND ARKADIN. JUST NOT SO MURDEROUS AND NOT SO ABLE AT KILLING WHOLE UNIVERSES.“
„Uh… thanks… I guess…“, shrugged Kayel. „So, are we done here?“
Nyssi shrugged. She grabbed her camera and took a few photos of the now definitely dead creatures. Then she pulled out her favorite weapon, the ornate god-of-death dagger, and began cutting off one of the creature's horns. She then moved on to the second one. But as Nyssi was just finishing, the creatures suddenly caught fire and transformed into a pile of ash within seconds. The same thing happened to the horns that Nyssi had cut off.
„Well, that's simultaneously practical and impractical…“, sighed Nyssi. „But at least I have the photos, hopefully.“
